* {{cite web | last =Brown | first =	Mark | title =MIT radar technology gives X-ray vision through concrete walls | work =Wired: Technology | publisher =Condé Nast UK | date =2011-10-19 | url = https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-10/19/mit-xray-vision | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web | last =Hibbard | first =Laura | title =MIT's New Radar Technology Lets You See Through Walls (VIDEO) | work =The Huffington Post: Tech | publisher =TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc. | date =2011-10-19 | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/18/mit-radar-technology-see-through-walls-_n_1018593.html | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web | last =Robinson | first =Martin | title =Researchers create scanner that lets soldiers in the battlefield see through walls | work =Mail Online | publisher =Associated Newspapers Ltd. | date =2011-10-21 | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2051392/MIT-researchers-create-scanner-lets-soldiers-walls.html?ito=feeds-newsxml | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web	 | title =Seeing through walls | work =Lincoln Laboratory: News | publisher =Massachusetts Institute of Technology | date =June 2011 | url = http://www.ll.mit.edu/news/thruwallradar.html | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}</ref> and his project-based MIT short-course on radar, where each student builds their own radar system.<ref name="hackaday2013-10-05">{{cite web | last =Harrison | first =	Todd | title =Homebuilt Ultra Wideband Impulse Radar | work =Hack a day | publisher =Hack a day | date =2013-10-05 | url = http://hackaday.com/2013/10/05/homebuilt-ultra-wideband-impulse-radar/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Szczyz |first=Mike |title=Hackaday Links: September 29, 2013 |work=Hackaday Links |publisher=Hack a day |date=2013-09-29 |url=http://hackaday.com/2013/09/29/hackaday-links-september-29-2013/ |accessdate=2013-10-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210509/http://hackaday.com/2013/09/29/hackaday-links-september-29-2013/ |archivedate=October 29, 2013 }}
* http://idealab.talkingpointsmemo.com/2011/10/mit-see-through-wall-radar-technology-can-track-you-breathing.php</ref>  This radar course has been adopted by numerous other universities and institutions. Charvat is also well known in the hacker and maker community for developing radar devices and imaging systems in his garage.<ref name=" hackaday2013-10-05"/><ref>Additional references regarding Charvat's home-built radar devices and imaging systems:
* {{cite web | last =Szczys | first =	Mike | title =Hacking the R-390A military shortwave radio receiver to transmit as well | work =Hack a day | publisher =Hack a day | date =2013-06-06 | url = http://hackaday.com/2013/06/06/hacking-the-r-390a-military-shortwave-radio-receiver-to-transmit-as-well/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web | last =Szczys | first =Mike | title =More continuous wave radar fun | work =Hack a day | publisher =Hack a day | date =2012-11-20 | url = http://hackaday.com/2012/11/20/more-continuous-wave-radar-fun/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web | last =Baichtal | first =John | title=Hacking a Police Radar | work =Make: Electronics | publisher =Maker Media | date =2012-11-12 | url = http://makezine.com/2012/11/12/hacking-a-police-radar/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web | last =Szczys | first =	Mike | title =Hacking an old radar gun to interface with a laptop | work =Hack a day | publisher =Hack a day | date =2012-11-01 | url = http://hackaday.com/2012/11/01/hacking-an-old-radar-gun-to-interface-with-a-laptop/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web | last =Ragan | first =	Sean Michael | title =Radar Gun Connected to Stereo System | work =Make: Education, Electronics, Science | publisher =Maker Media | date =2012-06-04 | url = http://makezine.com/2012/06/04/radar-gun-connected-to-stereo-system/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web | title =The ARRL Homebrew Challenge III -- And the Winner Is... | work =www.arrl.org: News | publisher =ARRL, the national association for Amateur Radio | date =2012-03-13 | url = http://www.arrl.org/news/the-arrl-homebrew-challenge-iii-and-the-winner-is | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
* {{cite web | last =Ragan | first =	Sean Michale | title =First Pictures From the Pegboard Phased Arrar Radar | work =Make: Art & Design, Electronics | publisher =Make Media | date =2012-01-25 | url = http://makezine.com/2012/01/25/first-pictures-from-the-pegboard-phased-array-radar/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}
*{{cite web | last =Ragan | first =	Sean Michael | title =DIY Phased Array Radar From Pegboard and Wi-Fi Antennas | work =Make: Art & Design, Electronics | publisher =Make Media | date =2012-01-24 | url = http://blog.makezine.com/2012/01/24/diy-phased-array-radar-from-pegboard-and-wi-fi-antennas/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}</ref>

Charvat grew up in the metro Detroit area, where he would take apart old televisions & radios. He built amateur radio equipment in high school, a [[radio telescope]] for which he won second place at the 1997 International Science and Engineering Fair in Louisville, KY, and developed many [[Radar engineering details|radar sensors]] in college. He earned PhD (2007),<ref name=" hackaday2013-10-05"/><ref>{{cite web | last =Baichtal | first =	John | title =Gregory Charvat's Radar Dissertation Now Online | work =Make: Electronics | date =2013-01-22 | url = http://makezine.com/2013/01/22/gregory-charvats-radar-dissertation-now-online/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}</ref> MSc (2003), and BSc (2002) degrees in electrical engineering from [[Michigan State University]].<ref name=" hackaday2013-10-05"/> He was a member of the technical staff at [[Lincoln Laboratory|MIT Lincoln Laboratory]] from Sept 2007 to Nov 2011, and has taught short radar courses at MIT where his ‘Build a Small Radar Sensor...’ course was top-ranked MIT Professional Education course in 2011.<ref name=" hackaday2013-10-05"/><ref name="IEEE2013-10-24">{{cite web | last =Karlin | first =Susan | title =Part-time Passions: Breathing New Life Into Old Things | work =the institute: People: Part-Time Passions | publisher =IEEE | date =2011-12-06 | url = http://theinstitute.ieee.org/people/hobbies/breathing-new-life-into-old-things | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}</ref>

Charvat has authored or co-authored numerous journals, proceedings, magazine articles, and seminars on topics including applied [[Electromagnetism|electromagnetics]], [[synthetic aperture radar]] (SAR), and [[Radar#Phased array|phased array]] radar systems, [[radio frequency]] (RF) and [[Analog signal|analog]] design. He has developed numerous rail SAR imaging sensors, phased array radar systems, [[History of radar#Impulse Radar|impulse radar]] systems and other radar sensors, and as well has designed his own amateur radio station. Charvat won best 2010 paper at the Military Sensing Symposia (MSS) Tri-Services Radar Symposium for his work on through wall radar.<ref name=" E.FinnMITnews"/>  For fun he develops vacuum tube audio equipment and restores antique radios and watches, among hobbies.<ref name="IEEE2013-10-24"/><ref>{{cite web | last =Benchoff | first =Brian | title =Frankenstein, an all-tube home theater amplifier | work =Hack a day | publisher =Hack a day | date =2013-01-02 | url = http://hackaday.com/2013/01/02/frankenstein-an-all-tube-home-theater-amplifier/ | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}</ref>

'''**Update March 27, 2014**'''

Recently, Gregory Charvat provided explanations of advanced sensing technologies that the general public could understand during a series of interviews on the missing Malaysian Flight 370 in March 2014:

http://www.cbsnews.com/videos/flight-370-search-using-state-of-the-art-sonar-and-radar-tech/

http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/03/21/pmt-bill-weir-malaysia-airlines-missing-flight-370.cnn.html

http://edition.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/03/18/pmt-greg-charvat.cnn.html

Sky News Television on Sunday morning 3/23/14 (afternoon in UK).

Malaysia's local NPR-style radio station Business FM 89.9, on 3/24/14.

Newstalk1010 Moore in the Morning with John Moore (Toronto Canada) on 3/24/14

The Arlene Bynon Show on SiriusXM Canada on 3/18/14.

Gregory Charvat is also a contributing author to Hack-a-Day blog, writing on the subject of using small radar technology for your next project
http://hackaday.com/2014/02/24/guest-post-try-radar-for-your-next-project/

and how Synthetic Aperture Radar imaging works:
http://hackaday.com/2014/03/17/radar-imaging-in-your-garage-synthetic-aperture-radar/

Gregory L. Charvat is a visiting research scientist at MIT Media Lab.

Charvat is the Series Editor of the, "Modern and Practical Approaches to Electrical Engineering," book series. Author Albert Sabban published the most recent part in the series, "Low-Visibility Antennas for Communication Systems," on September 18, 2015.

Low-Visibility Antennas for Communication Systems is currently available for purchase here:

https://www.crcpress.com/Low-Visibility-Antennas-for-Communication-Systems/Sabban/9781482246438

