==External links== {{wikiquote|Hotel Hell}} *{{Official website|http://www.fox.com/hotelhell}}
{{Gordon Ramsay}}
[[Category:2012 American television series debuts]] [[Category:2016 American television series endings]] [[Category:2010s American reality television series]] [[Category:English-language television programs]] [[Category:Fox network shows]] [[Category:Hotels in the United States]] [[Category:Television shows featuring audio description]] [[Category:Workplace television series]]

'''Human Longevity''' is a [[San Diego]]-based venture launched by [[Craig Venter]] and [[Peter Diamandis]] in 2013. Its goal is to build the world's most comprehensive database on human genotypes and phenotypes, and then subject it to machine learning so that it can help develop new ways to fight [[Aging-associated diseases|diseases associated with aging]].<ref name="MyUser_Wired.co.uk_July_8_2015c">{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2015-04/24/brad-perkins-human-longevity-wired-health-2015 |title='Supercharged' genomics: 100 years of breakthroughs possible in 10 years (Wired UK) |newspaper=Wired.co.uk |date=  |author= |accessdate= July 8, 2015}}</ref> The company received {{usd|80 million}} in investments in its Series A offering in summer 2014 and announced a further $220 million Series B investment offering in April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.humanlongevity.com/human-longevity-inc-completes-220-million-series-b-financing/|title=Human Longevity, Inc. Completes $220 Million Series B Financing –  Human Longevity, Inc.|website=www.humanlongevity.com|access-date=2016-08-17}}</ref> It has made deals with drug companies [[Celgene]] and [[AstraZeneca]] to collaborate in its research.

While it is conducting research, the company is offering a wellness service known as "Health Nucleus," which offers customers a range of medical tests such as a full genome sequencing and tests for early indications of [[Cancer|cancers]], [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer's]] and [[Cardiovascular disease|heart disease]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21704788-fight-cheat-death-hotting-up-adding-ages|title=Adding ages|newspaper=The Economist|issn=0013-0613|access-date=2016-08-17}}</ref> This testing is meant to help people catch diseases earlier than otherwise possible and to identify risk factors for diseases later in life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/07/19/this-biotech-wants-to-radically-extend-human-lifespan.html|title=Biotech says longer life is in your DNA|last=Ferris|first=Robert|date=2016-07-19|website=CNBC|access-date=2016-08-17}}</ref> 

At the start of 2017 the company hired Cynthia Collins from GE Healthcare, and Venter became Executive Chair.  The company's chief operating office, Mark Winham, left the company in mid-2017, and Collins and the company's chief medical officer, Brad Perkins, left in December.  Venter stepped back into the CEO role, but announced in May 2018 that he was leaving the company to return to the J. Craig Venter Institute.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Nick Paul |title=Venter to leave Human Longevity as turnover at the top continues |url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/biotech/venter-to-leave-human-longevity-as-turnover-at-top-continues|work=FierceBiotech |date=May 30, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

